<!-- Article Content -->
  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
      <p>The gospel spread quickly, as fitness gospels do.</p>

      <p>Dr. Peter Attia put Zone 2 training at the center of <em>Outlive</em>, his best-selling book on longevity. Dr. Inigo San Millan, a physiologist at the University of Colorado who has trained Tour de France winners, appeared on seemingly every major health podcast explaining that low-intensity aerobic exercise — specifically, exercise below the first lactate threshold — was the sweet spot for mitochondrial adaptation. The logic was compelling: elite endurance athletes spend roughly 80% of their training time at low intensity. Elite athletes have exceptional mitochondrial function. Therefore, low-intensity training produces exceptional mitochondria.</p>

      <p>By 2024, Zone 2 had become, for the wellness-educated professional class, what counting steps had been for an earlier generation and what cold plunges would be for the next: the specific, semi-technical prescription that meant you were taking your longevity seriously. Heart rate monitors. Lactate meters. Careful attention to staying below the threshold.</p>

      <p>In July 2025, a narrative review published in <em>Sports Medicine</em> by researchers at Queen's University and McMaster University — institutions with legitimate exercise physiology pedigrees — examined the actual evidence for Zone 2's claimed superiority. Their conclusion was not what the podcasts had been saying.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="what-zone-2-is" class="reveal">
      <h2>What Zone 2 Is</h2>

      <p>First, clarity on terms, because the Zone 2 conversation has been hampered from the start by definitional inconsistency.</p>

      <p>"Zone 2" refers to a training intensity below the first lactate threshold (LT1) — the exercise intensity at which blood lactate begins to rise measurably above resting levels. This is typically described as a conversational pace: you can speak in complete sentences but are clearly working. Heart rate in this zone varies significantly between individuals and is influenced by fitness level, age, and the specific heart rate model being used. The popular five-zone model used by most consumer wearables places Zone 2 at roughly 60-70% of maximum heart rate, but this is an approximation that can be substantially wrong for any given individual.</p>

      <p>At Zone 2 intensity, the body relies primarily on aerobic fat oxidation for energy — the mitochondria are working steadily, and lactate, rather than accumulating, is being used as fuel by muscles and the heart. This is where San Millan's metabolic framework becomes most specific: he defines Zone 2 by the metabolic signature, not the heart rate, which is the correct scientific framing even if it requires more sophisticated measurement to implement.</p>

      <p>The claimed benefits: Zone 2 training uniquely stimulates mitochondrial biogenesis, improves fat oxidation capacity, and trains the aerobic base that supports all other intensities. All of these are real adaptations. The question is whether Zone 2 uniquely and optimally produces them.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="athletes-fallacy" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Athletes Fallacy</h2>

      <p>The Queen's University review identified the central evidentiary problem with Zone 2 advocacy: the foundational observation is correlational, derived from elite athletes, and may not mean what it's assumed to mean.</p>

      <p>Elite endurance athletes — Tour de France cyclists, marathon runners, cross-country skiers — spend roughly 80% of their training time at low intensity (Zone 2 or below) and 20% at high intensity. They also have the highest mitochondrial densities of any population ever measured. The leap from this observation to "Zone 2 causes high mitochondrial density" has been the engine driving the entire framework.</p>

      <p>But elite athletes aren't spending 80% of their time in Zone 2 because Zone 2 is maximally efficient for mitochondrial adaptation. They're spending 80% of their time in Zone 2 because they train 15-25 hours per week, and they have to manage fatigue, injury risk, and training load across that volume. At those hours, high-intensity training cannot dominate without breaking the body down. The polarised training model — low intensity most of the time, very high intensity a minority of the time — is a strategy for managing very high total training load, not a prescription for what intensity is physiologically optimal when time is limited.</p>

      <p>The general population person training 5-7 hours per week has no such constraint. The reasoning that applies to a professional athlete accumulating 20 hours is not straightforwardly applicable to the person fitting in four 75-minute sessions.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"Elite athletes aren't spending 80% of their time in Zone 2 because Zone 2 is maximally efficient for mitochondrial adaptation. They're doing it because they train 15-25 hours per week, and they have to manage fatigue."</p>
    </aside>

    <section id="what-review-found" class="reveal">
      <h2>What the Review Found</h2>

      <p>The review conducted a systematic evaluation of the evidence for Zone 2's claimed unique effects on mitochondrial capacity in non-athlete populations.</p>

      <p><strong>On mitochondrial biogenesis:</strong> The primary signalling pathway through which exercise drives mitochondrial biogenesis is AMPK activation, which triggers PGC-1a — the "master regulator" of mitochondrial biogenesis. The review found that Zone 2 intensity produces modest AMPK activation, while higher intensities (above LT1, into Zone 3 and above) produce substantially greater AMPK activation, greater calcium flux, greater mechanical stress, and additional signalling through pathways that Zone 2 does not adequately stimulate. When studies directly compare mitochondrial adaptations at matched training volumes, higher intensities produce equal or greater increases in mitochondrial markers.</p>

      <p><strong>On fat oxidation capacity:</strong> Zone 2 training does increase maximal fat oxidation rate, consistently. But so does higher-intensity training. The review found no strong evidence that Zone 2 is superior to higher intensities for improving fat oxidation when training volume is equated. The Zone 2 advantage here appears to be primarily a volume story — spending more total time in the fat-oxidising intensity range produces more adaptation to fat oxidation, but this is an argument for duration, not specifically for staying below LT1.</p>

      <p><strong>On cardiorespiratory fitness (VO2 max):</strong> VO2 max is the single strongest predictor of all-cause mortality in the exercise literature. The review found clear evidence that higher-intensity training is superior to Zone 2 for improving VO2 max, particularly at the training volumes most people realistically achieve. The ACSM physical activity guidelines, the review noted, already acknowledge that higher intensities may be required to improve cardiovascular fitness — a concession that the Zone 2 advocates have largely glossed over.</p>

      <p>The review's most pointed conclusion: people who replace higher-intensity exercise with Zone 2 exercise, believing they are optimising for longevity, may actually be reducing the cardiometabolic benefits they'd otherwise receive.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
      <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">Key Findings from the Sports Medicine Review</h4>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
        <li><strong>Mitochondrial biogenesis:</strong> Higher intensities produce greater AMPK activation and equal or greater mitochondrial adaptations</li>
        <li><strong>Fat oxidation:</strong> Zone 2 improves it, but so does higher-intensity training — no unique Zone 2 advantage when volume is matched</li>
        <li><strong>VO2 max:</strong> Higher-intensity training is clearly superior — the single strongest predictor of all-cause mortality</li>
        <li><strong>Net effect:</strong> Replacing higher-intensity work with Zone 2 may reduce overall cardiometabolic benefit</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <section id="proponents-response" class="reveal">
      <h2>What Zone 2 Proponents Say Back</h2>

      <p>The review is not the end of the conversation. Its own limitations deserve acknowledgment.</p>

      <p>It is a narrative review, not a meta-analysis. Narrative reviews reflect the judgment of their authors in selecting and interpreting studies, which introduces scope for bias in either direction. The authors were candid about this limitation.</p>

      <p>San Millan and others have argued that the review mischaracterises the Zone 2 framework, which never claimed Zone 2 was the only intensity one should ever train, but rather that it should form the aerobic base of a broader programme — that without an adequate Zone 2 base, higher-intensity work is less productive and more injurious. This is a defensible position with some supportive evidence, particularly in athlete populations.</p>

      <p>There is also a practical argument the review doesn't fully engage with: for many people, Zone 2 is the intensity they can sustain long enough to accumulate meaningful training volume. High-intensity interval training is excellent per minute; it is also demanding enough that many people will do less of it, quit sooner, or injure themselves more readily. A training protocol with excellent theoretical efficiency but poor real-world adherence is not the optimal protocol.</p>

      <p>The Zone 2 community is also correct that the cellular metabolic adaptations San Millan has documented in type 2 diabetic patients and metabolically compromised individuals are real — improving the mitochondrial function and fat oxidation capacity in these populations is genuinely important, and Zone 2 training does this. The disagreement is about whether Zone 2 is uniquely effective for this purpose, not whether it is effective.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"A training protocol with excellent theoretical efficiency but poor real-world adherence is not the optimal protocol."</p>
    </aside>

    <section id="honest-synthesis" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Honest Synthesis</h2>

      <p>The Zone 2 discussion has been a casualty of the podcast-to-practice pipeline, in which nuanced exercise physiology designed for elite athletic programming gets transmitted through influential communicators into prescriptions for non-athletes as though the context is identical.</p>

      <p>What the evidence, including the 2025 review, actually supports:</p>

      <p><strong>Zone 2 training is good.</strong> Low-intensity aerobic exercise produces real metabolic adaptations, is accessible to most people, carries low injury risk, can be sustained for long durations, and has excellent evidence for cardiovascular and metabolic health. None of this is in dispute.</p>

      <p><strong>Zone 2 is not uniquely optimal.</strong> For people with limited training time — the majority of the population — higher-intensity exercise produces greater mitochondrial and cardiovascular adaptations per unit of time. The prescription "more Zone 2 and less higher-intensity work" is not supported by the evidence as a net positive trade for most people.</p>

      <p><strong>A mixed-intensity approach has the best evidence.</strong> A programme that includes meaningful time at higher intensities (whether traditional threshold training, tempo work, or interval protocols) alongside moderate-intensity aerobic work produces superior outcomes to either extreme. This is sometimes called polarised training when the mix skews toward low and high, with less in the moderate middle — but the specific distribution matters less than the principle: some high-intensity work is essential, and removing it in favour of pure Zone 2 is a step backward.</p>

      <p><strong>The best exercise is the exercise you actually do.</strong> This is not a cop-out. Adherence is the dominant variable in long-term exercise outcomes, and any honest discussion of exercise prescription has to account for it. If Zone 2 is the intensity someone will sustain as a habit, its superior adherence properties may outweigh its modest inferiority in per-session physiological signal. If the same person would enjoy and sustain higher-intensity workouts equally, the higher-intensity version is the better recommendation.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="practical-picture" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Practical Picture</h2>

      <p>For someone building or improving an exercise programme with health and longevity in mind, the current evidence supports something like this:</p>

      <p><strong>Cardiovascular training</strong> that includes sessions at moderate intensity (Zone 2 and above) for the aerobic base and sessions at higher intensity — whether sustained threshold work or shorter intervals — that meaningfully challenge the cardiovascular system. A rough guide: most people should be working hard enough at some point in the week to make conversation difficult. If every session is a comfortable walk or a gentle jog, the cardiometabolic adaptation signal is being undersold.</p>

      <p><strong>Resistance training</strong> — which the Zone 2 conversation has often crowded out — with consistent evidence for all-cause mortality reduction, metabolic health, insulin sensitivity, bone density, and functional independence. For most people, the gap in their programme is resistance training, not insufficient low-intensity aerobic work.</p>

      <p><strong>Consistency over intensity optimisation.</strong> The difference between exercising regularly at a range of intensities and obsessing over zone calibration is small compared to the difference between exercising regularly and not exercising at all.</p>

      <p>The Zone 2 conversation has done real good by drawing attention to aerobic fitness as a longevity variable and motivating a generation of people to move more. Where it went wrong was the step from "low-intensity aerobic training is important" to "low-intensity aerobic training is the optimal intensity, and you should build your programme around maximising time in Zone 2." The evidence didn't support that step then. It supports it even less now.</p>
    </section>

